<subSubSection id="DC735594722880CA5AA815C7F7317743" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="description">
<paragraph id="1895565AEAD538608ABAA30C217002FA" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph id="35B7E86393DE4EF02853CCCC4BE3CC0A" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
(Fig. 4A). Alive blackish outside and greyish inside (in alcohol chocolate brown throughout). Shape massively encrusting, flat with smooth surface, no apparent oscules; inhalant openings in sieve plates. Consistency cheesy, slightly compressible. A representative size of preserved specimens is 5
<normalizedToken id="5EE28C50651564F1D1FEE7951BBD422E" originalValue="×4×">x4x</normalizedToken>
0.7 cm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF963D1BB7EF7AE0F763ADFF4557BEDD" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Skeleton: a layer of microscleres overlying a loose mass of calthrops megascleres. Spicular density appears lower than in the specimens from the British Isles.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2D34890F372F51C185E1997B6F6FF226" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Spicules: calthrops, toxas, sanidasters.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DAB0118D471A8000ACF6EF7EA173FB15" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Calthrops (Fig. 4B), relatively uniform in size, cladi of irregular outline with endings irregularly stair-stepped and/or malformed, occasionally one or more cladi lacking; 58
<normalizedToken id="30BE670447E1D7FBA8E3814C205CE4BF" originalValue="–108.3–">-108.3-</normalizedToken>
165 
<normalizedToken id="481276FE312E3B19CC806A239558EF64" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5
<normalizedToken id="286E29AD291941EEEF695AB030125567" originalValue="–14.6–">-14.6-</normalizedToken>
27 
<normalizedToken id="17702EA8122E5A71D36FC334A1405A62" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, cladome 110
<normalizedToken id="CFBA9D18D0AC3497C46D6D67E7ACB2F3" originalValue="–159.3–">-159.3-</normalizedToken>
240 
<normalizedToken id="24E07528FDEFD35AAE9468D8019F854F" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E3121D541D9280DFFC9FA4C5A8D9F85F" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Toxa-like microscleres (Figs 4
<normalizedToken id="BD4AAA939D1F240A95250EDE1200E69C" originalValue="C–D">C-D</normalizedToken>
), symmetrical, smooth, but slightly undulate / polytylote, with a shallow curve and evenly pointed; 37
<normalizedToken id="4709253E860358FF6E9E2B254E28B22C" originalValue="–51.3–69×">-51.3-69x</normalizedToken>
0.5
<normalizedToken id="CC9F64EC7B168492AB6195C7496CD782" originalValue="–0.7–">-0.7-</normalizedToken>
1.5 
<normalizedToken id="0EBEB5041FC23174EBC9CBFA735A7C31" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5F02B55ABC1E93CA96C908443C85B11E" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Sanidasters (Fig. 4E), rather uniform in size and shape, spines relatively long and thin, occasionally with a somewhat irregular shape; 16
<normalizedToken id="07F91D6C43DEF551AAB55458DDA48E8B" originalValue="–19.3–">-19.3-</normalizedToken>
24 
<normalizedToken id="FF697D7139513ACDE18BFBB29ECDA625" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5
<normalizedToken id="CF467DD128F6BFD5EAA5378166784F35" originalValue="–2.4–">-2.4-</normalizedToken>
6 
<normalizedToken id="447446CA9BAB853B273E3AE1187B1DB9" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
(including spines).
</paragraph>
<caption id="CD7E62A95065EC013ED9945F77B5647F" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
